An Analysis of City of Chicago Employee Salaries

Brian Wang

July 2017

This data was obtained from https://www.datazar.com/file/f028ce9b8-6782-4d6d-9df1-743f8dca76a2 and accessed June 2017. The city of Chicago also provides a slightly more raw (and possibly more recently updated) version of this dataset here.

This dataset includes names, titles, departments, and salary information for all employees of the city of Chicago. Today, Im going to import the data, perform some analyses and create some data visualizations.

# Multiple plot function
#
# ggplot objects can be passed in ..., or to plotlist (as a list of ggplot objects)
# - cols:   Number of columns in layout
# - layout: A matrix specifying the layout. If present, 'cols' is ignored.
#
# If the layout is something like matrix(c(1,2,3,3), nrow=2, byrow=TRUE),
# then plot 1 will go in the upper left, 2 will go in the upper right, and
# 3 will go all the way across the bottom.
#
multiplot <- function(..., plotlist=NULL, file, cols=1, layout=NULL) {
  library(grid)

  # Make a list from the ... arguments and plotlist
  plots <- c(list(...), plotlist)

  numPlots = length(plots)

  # If layout is NULL, then use 'cols' to determine layout
  if (is.null(layout)) {
    # Make the panel
    # ncol: Number of columns of plots
    # nrow: Number of rows needed, calculated from # of cols
    layout <- matrix(seq(1, cols * ceiling(numPlots/cols)),
                    ncol = cols, nrow = ceiling(numPlots/cols))
  }

 if (numPlots==1) {
    print(plots[[1]])

  } else {
    # Set up the page
    grid.newpage()
    pushViewport(viewport(layout = grid.layout(nrow(layout), ncol(layout))))

    # Make each plot, in the correct location
    for (i in 1:numPlots) {
      # Get the i,j matrix positions of the regions that contain this subplot
      matchidx <- as.data.frame(which(layout == i, arr.ind = TRUE))

      print(plots[[i]], vp = viewport(layout.pos.row = matchidx$row,
                                      layout.pos.col = matchidx$col))
    }
  }
}

We examine the dimensions and head of the dataset to see that we have 32062 observations with these 4 variables each. We also see that the salary column should be converted to a numeric data type, but we first need to strip away the punctuation.

# Convert salary variable to double after stripping away punctuation
salaries$salary <- str_replace(salaries$salary, "\\$", "")
salaries$salary <- str_replace(salaries$salary, ",", "")
salaries$salary <- as.double(salaries$salary)
# Alternate way to convert using single expression / regex
# salaries$salary <- as.double(
#  gsub("^\\$([1234567890]*),*([1234567890]*)\\.([1234567890]*)$", "\\1\\2\\.\\3", salaries$salary))

# use regex to parse name column
names <- salaries$name

salaries <- salaries %>%
  separate(col = name,
           into = c("last", "first"),
           sep = ", ") %>%
  extract(col = first,
          into = c("first", "middle"),
          "([ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ]+)[ ]*([ABCDEFHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ]*)")

salaries$name <- names

# if no middle name, fill middle field with NA
salaries$middle <- gsub("^$", NA, salaries$middle)

Whats the mean, median, range of salaries in the city of Chicago?

## # ... with 3 more variables: name <chr>, firstletter <chr>,
## #   last_firstletter <chr>

The city employee that makes the most is Ginger Evans, who makes an annual salary of $300,000 as the commissioner of aviation. Evans oversees both of the major international airports in Chicago, OHare and Midway International Airport.

The city employee that makes the least is Steven Koch, who is listed as an administrative secretary in the mayors office on a salary of $0.96/year. At first I thought that this was a mistake, but turns out that its not. Steven Koch is a former investment banker that assumed the deputy mayors position in 2012 to improve Chicagos financial situation and attract new businesses to the city. He stated that his interest in the position was not about the salary, but about giving back. More information can be found at http://chicago.cbslocal.com/2012/08/06/new-deputy-mayor-to-work-on-improving-economy-for-just-1-per-year/.

Since Steven Koch is a bit of an outlier, lets also make sure to look into whos the second lowest paid employee. Turns out these are all employees in the Dept. of Family & Support, either working as foster grandparents or senior companions.

plot(density(salaries$salary), main="Distribution of Chicago city employee salaries")

Plotting the density of employees salaries and examining the summary statistics, we also observe a few things.

  • The distribution has multiple peaks, which Im assuming may be due to standard salary schedules for certain positions
  • Most of the distribution is concentrated around the mean. The distribution doesnt exhibit any unusually strange patterns.
  • The few employees with extremely high-salaries like Ginger Evans do not really skew the overall mean; in fact, the median salary is higher than the mean salary.

Relationships between variables

Now that weve spent some time looking at each variable individually, we can try to explore some relationships between variables, for example -

  • What department costs Chicago the most in terms of total salary paid?
  • What department costs Chicago the most in terms of highest average salary per employee?
  • Grouped by the letter your first name starts with, what letter has the highest average salary?

We start by computing the total salary paid per department and computing some summary statistics on salary by department.

# Total salary paid per department (annual)
(salaries_summary <- salaries %>%
  group_by(dept) %>%
  summarise(sum = sum(salary), n = n(), mean = round(mean(salary), 2), sd = round(sd(salary), 2)) %>%
  arrange(desc(sd))) %>% datatable()

The city of Chicago spends $2.6 billion on employee salaries annually. Of this, about $1.1 billion is spent on the police department and about $459 million is spent on the fire department.

If we look at the average salary per employee, the Department of Innovation and Technology (DoIT) has the highest mean salary of $96,727.29 with the buildings and fire department with the second and third highest mean salary.

As for a standard deviation of employee salaries within a department, the highest is in the mayors office, while the lowest is in the human relations (resources?) department. Other departments with a high standard deviation of salaries include the Family & Support department and Law department.

The police department actually has the third lowest standard deviation of departments in the dataset, most likely because of a standard salary schedule for officers.

Im a bit curious about the high standard deviation of salaries in the mayors office, so lets filter the salaries by the mayors office and sort/plot.

# reminder: things that themes can modify: axes, legend, plot, panel, and strips (facet)
salaries %>%
  filter(dept == "MAYOR'S OFFICE") %>%
  mutate(pos = salary) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(name, salary), y = salary, fill = salary)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  geom_text(aes(x = name, y = salary, label = name),
            color = "white",
            check_overlap = TRUE,
            na.rm = TRUE,
            size = 2, hjust = 1.1) + 
  geom_text(aes(x = name, y = salary, label = salary),
            color = "black",
            check_overlap = TRUE,
            na.rm = TRUE,
            size = 2,
            hjust = -0.2) +
  scale_y_continuous(expand = c(0.01, 0), limits = c(0, 225000)) + 
  coord_flip() +
  ggtitle("employee salaries, chicago mayor's office") + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(),
        axis.text.y = element_blank(),
        axis.ticks.y = element_blank(),
        axis.title.y = element_blank(),
        panel.background = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor = element_line(color = "gray80"),
        panel.ontop = FALSE, # puts gridlines on top of data
        plot.background = element_rect(fill = "white", color = "black"),
        panel.border = element_rect(linetype = "dashed", fill = NA),
        legend.position = "none")

We can see that the mayor, Rahm Emanuel, makes the most by far. Also, we are reminded of the reason for the extremely high standard deviation - we have Steven Koch, whos only making $0.96.

So the mayors office has the second highest-paid city employee (the mayor) and the lowest paid employee (Steven Koch), which is why we see the highest standard deviation in this department.

Okay, so weve spent some time understanding how salaries vary within departments, and have an idea now of which departments are most costly to the city of Chicago. Lets finish up by answering our quirky but possibly interesting question:

Grouped by first letter of first name, what letter earns the highest average salary?

(salary_fname <- salaries %>%
  group_by("First Letter of First Name" = firstletter) %>%
  summarise("Average Salary" = round(mean(salary), 2)) %>%
  arrange(desc(`Average Salary`))) %>%
  datatable()
salary_fname %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(`First Letter of First Name`, `Average Salary`), y = `Average Salary`, fill = `Average Salary`)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity") + 
  ggtitle("average salary of chicago city employees, grouped by first letter of first name") +
  scale_y_continuous(expand=c(0,0)) +
  theme(axis.title.x = element_blank(),
        plot.title = element_text(),
        panel.background = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor = element_line(color = "gray80"),
        panel.ontop = FALSE, # puts gridlines on top of data
        plot.background = element_rect(fill = "white", color = "black"),
        panel.border = element_rect(linetype = "dashed", fill = NA),
        legend.justification = "top")

Well, at least it doesnt appear the city of Chicago is discriminating against people based on the letter that their first name starts with, at least in general.

Average salary, by first letter of last name

(salary_lname <- salaries %>%
  group_by("First Letter of Last Name" = last_firstletter) %>%
  summarise("Average Salary" = round(mean(salary), 2)) %>%
  arrange(desc(`Average Salary`))) %>%
  datatable()
salary_lname %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(`First Letter of Last Name`, `Average Salary`), y = `Average Salary`, fill = `Average Salary`)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity") + 
  ggtitle("average salary of chicago city employees, grouped by first letter of last name") +
  scale_y_continuous(expand=c(0,0)) +
  theme(axis.title.x = element_blank(),
        plot.title = element_text(),
        panel.background = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor = element_line(color = "gray80"),
        panel.ontop = FALSE, # puts gridlines on top of data
        plot.background = element_rect(fill = "white", color = "black"),
        panel.border = element_rect(linetype = "dashed", fill = NA),
        legend.justification = "top")
